Here we provide a derivation of the analytic form for 
the inverse of a class of matrices $A(a,b,c,d)$ 
defined in \refeqn{A}.
First we introduce notation, shorthand, and preliminary
results in \refsec{ABCnotation}.
We also use many common linear algebra results 
throughout, and references for these can be found in 
\citet{Halmos1958,Brookes2011}.




\section{Notation and Preliminary Results}
\label{sec:ABCnotation}


\subsection{$A(a,b,c,d)$}

We will be interested in matrices of the form
\begin{equation}
A(a,b,c,d) = \left [ \begin{array}{cc}
    a\text{I}_{b\times b} & \bm{1}_{b \times d} \\
		\bm{1}_{b \times d} & c\text{I}_{d\times d}
	\end{array} \right ] = \left [ \begin{array}{cccccccc}
	a & 0 & 0 & 0 & 1 & 1 & \hdots & 1 \\
	0 & a & 0 & 0 & 1 & 1 & \hdots & 1 \\
	\vdots & & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots & & \ddots & \vdots \\
	0 & 0 & 0 & a & 1 & 1 & \hdots & 1 \\
	1 & 1 & 1 & 1 & c & 0 & \hdots & 0 \\
	1 & 1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & c & \hdots & 0 \\
	\vdots & & & \vdots & \vdots & & \ddots & \vdots \\
	1 & 1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 & \hdots & c \\
	\end{array} \right ].
\label{eqn:A}
\end{equation}
